          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>
              Summary: Demonstrations in Angola turn violent amid economic
              frustration and corruption.
            </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> At least four were killed, and over 500
            people were arrested amid violent protests in Angola over the
            government‚Äôs decision to eliminate fuel subsidies and hike diesel
            market value. Demonstrators targeted shops, banks, and cars, and the
            police also reported cases of looting. The ANATA taxi association,
            which announced the three-day strike on Monday, condemned the
            violence but said the strike will continue.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The cause:</strong> The rising inflation and high
            unemployment (60% of youth are unemployed) have already been
            frustrating for many Angolans. Many blame the ruling party for
            decades of mismanagement and corruption. The country's
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h2-6-overdependence-on-its-oil-resources"
              target="_blank"
              >overdependence on its oil resources</a
            >
            has increased its vulnerability to external shocks. High adolescent
            pregnancy, maternal and neonatal deaths, and impaired growth show
            the need for capital spending on human resources.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The big picture:</strong> Critics, including well-known
            sociologists, argue that the government has neglected its citizens
            while the elites grow rich. A 2020 report titled Luanda Leaks calls
            out Isabel dos Santos, daughter of Angola‚Äôs former president, who
            accumulated
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-spotlight-h2-7-a-2b-fortune"
              target="_blank"
              >a $2B fortune</a
            >
            through decades of corrupt deals.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
