          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i
              >After the collapse of the government in 1990, Mongolia
              established a multi-party government and a market economy.
              Credits: Koryo Tours</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The difference:</strong> Mongolia is an independent country
            between Russia and China, which is often referred to as ‚ÄúOuter
            Mongolia.‚Äù Mongolia gained independence in 1921 with the help of the
            Soviets and was a dependent state under the Soviet Union until 1937.
            It became a democratic nation in 1990.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Inner Mongolia has been part of China since the Qing Dynasty
            expanded in the 17th century. While it maintains some cultural
            autonomy, the Han Chinese dominate the province by comprising 80% of
            the population (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-foundations-h1-16-read-more"
              target="_blank"
              >read more</a
            >).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The geopolitics:</strong> Mongolia is landlocked between
            China and Russia. It balances its economic ties to China, Russia,
            and Western democracies by maintaining a ‚Äú
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-foundations-h1-17-third-neighbor-policy"
              target="_blank"
              >third neighbor policy</a
            >, by staying neutral to maintain its sovereignty, and staying away
            from great-power rivalries.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            On the other hand, China tightly controls Inner Mongolia as it fears
            ethnic Mongol nationalism and wants to protect its resources.
            Tensions can occur periodically over cultural policies in Inner
            Mongolia. The Chinese officials have pushed for
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-foundations-h1-18-mandarin-language-education"
              target="_blank"
              >Mandarin-language education</a
            >, which has fueled protests.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The fun fact:</strong> Inner Mongolia is home to vast oil
            reserves and China‚Äôs most famous ghost city, Ordos. In the 1950s,
            China constructed the Genghis Khan Mausoleum in Inner Mongolia to
            incorporate Mongol heritage into its national history. However,
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-jul-25-foundations-h1-19-the-actual-burial-site"
              target="_blank"
              >the actual burial site</a
            >
            of Genghis Khan is still unknown.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Know more about the inner and outer Mongolias
            <a
